<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,487,513]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for Dr. Terry L. Erwin for his extensive collecting of insects using his insecticidal fogging technique in many tropical areas of the world which has immeasurably increased our knowledge of the composition and diversity of insects in the tropics.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,775]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,321,599,625]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</emphasis>
From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nielson" authorityYear="1983" box="[403,512,600,625]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gabrita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fistula">
<emphasis box="[403,512,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">G. fistula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs. 229, 233, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nielson, M. W." box="[723,886,600,626]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 78" refId="ref4086" refString="Nielson, M. W. (1983) A revision of the subfamily Coelidiinae (Homptera: Cicadellidae). Part V. New tribes Hikangiini, Youngolidiini, and Gabritini. Pacific Insects Monograph, 40, 1 - 78." type="journal article" year="1983">Nielson 1983</bibRefCitation>
) to which it is most similar, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nielson" authorityYear="2010" box="[1238,1349,600,625]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gabrita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erwini">
<emphasis box="[1238,1349,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">G. erwini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the pygofer without processes and by the pregenital plate, which has only a few setae apically. The configuration of the aedeagus is remarkably uniform among species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1858" box="[1184,1279,674,699]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gabrita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1279,674,699]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Gabrita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known from males (unknown for 
<taxonomicName box="[401,547,712,737]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gabrita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictifrons">
<emphasis box="[401,547,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">G. pictifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) but in 
<taxonomicName box="[644,794,712,737]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Petalopoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulipes">
<emphasis box="[644,794,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">G. annulipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the shaft is somewhat broader than in the other three species.
</paragraph>
